default4.default              defaultHistory of defaultLincoln Roaddefault Level Crossingdefault default&#xa0;
default4.1
default              
defaultWhen the construction of railways was authorised, mainly in the 19th century, the individual enabling Act of Parliament specified how the railway was to cross other ways (for example roads and footpaths), eit
defaulther by bridge or on the level. Where the crossing was on the level, the arrangements for protecting the users, both railway and highway, were specified.
default 
default&#xa0;
default4.2
default              
defaultThe railway to 
defaultEnfield
default 
defaultTown
default was constructed under powers contained in The Enfield and Edmonton Ju
defaultnction Railway Act 1846. The site of the level crossing 
defaultin what is now 
defaultLincoln Road
default 
defaultwas referenced as an 
defaultOccupation Road
default. 
defaultHowever, t
defaulthere is no power in the Authorising Act for the railway to cross the road at grade, which was a requirement for all railways
default authorised after s. 46 of the Railways Clauses Consolidation Act 1845 came into force. 
default&#xa0;
default4.3
default              
defaultNetwork Rail 
defaultrecords indicate 
defaultthat the 
defaultcrossing has been 
defaultstaffed 
defaultsince at least the late 1880s. Closure to vehicles at night is documented back to at least 1939, 
defaultbut it is presumed that the hours of manning were the result of a contractual agreement dating from the time when the land served by the level crossing w
defaultas agricultural
default.
default Network Rail argue that there are now no successors in title who may be entitled to us
defaulte the crossing as of right, the area having been built up many years ago.  Network Rail also highlight that t
defaulthe then 
defaultEnfield U
defaultrban District Council 
defaultwas advised of the crossing’s occupational status in June 1947
default. 
default&#xa0;
default4.4
default              
defaultNetwork Rail have confirmed that s
defaultigns describing the opening times of the crossing were recorded as present in 1956. The hours were proposed to be reduced to 0800–1800 Monday to Saturday 
defaultin 
defaultFebruary 1994, although manning appears to have reverted to 0600 to 1800 at some time after that. 
defaultN
defaultetwork Rail also argue that the 
defaultregular closure of the crossing to vehicles at night and on Sundays is evide
defaultnce that a right of way for vehicles cannot have been established.
